					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sirpudding" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(348648); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=348648&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250578" alt="sirpudding" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=348648)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sirpudding" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(348648); return false;" >sirpudding</a></span> <span class="odate time_1457383046 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Mar 2016 20:37</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2469048">
									

<p>This is a supremely entertaining yarn, and does two things better than any other single contest entry, I think:</p>
<ul>
<li>Sets up the MTF with a clear idea of their theme, their size, their service culture, their place in the Foundation as a whole and the specific characters that comprise it.</li>
<li>Seemlessy weaves the MTF into existing narrative threads and established characters.</li>
</ul>
<p>Of all the MTFs in the contest, I think Eta-11 is the one that I would be most likely to just <em>have</em> a use for at some point (rather than needing either some rather odd circumstances or convoluted narrative reasoning) and if a goal of the contest was to create new MTFs that would be modular elements for future authors, this is the most successful.</p>

							</div>

								
